# George Granville Leveson‑Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland  

**His Grace** [KG](/Order_of_the_Garter) [PC](/Her_Majesty%27s_Most_Honourable_Privy_Council) (9 January 1758 – 19 July 1833) was an English politician, diplomat, landowner and patron of the arts from the [Leveson‑Gower family](/Leveson-Gower_family). He was the eldest son of [Granville Leveson‑Gower, 1st Marquess of Stafford](/Granville_Leveson-Gower,_1st_Marquess_of_Stafford), by his second wife, Lady Louisa Egerton, and he inherited a title that would carry him through the turbulent decades of the late‑Georgian and early‑Victorian eras. Known by several subsidiary titles—[Viscount Trentham](/Viscount_Trentham) (1758–1786), [Earl Gower](/Earl_Gower) (1786–1803) and [Marquess of Stafford](/Marquess_of_Stafford) (1803–1833)—he ultimately became the **1st Duke of Sutherland**, a peerage created for him on 28 January 1833.  

His life was marked by considerable wealth, extensive political service, a controversial ambassadorship during the French Revolution, and a legacy forever stained by his role in the **Highland Clearances**. He remains a figure of both admiration and censure in British history.  

---  

## Background  

Sutherland was born in [London](/London) on 9 January 1758, the eldest son of [Granville Leveson‑Gower, 1st Marquess of Stafford](/Granville_Leveson-Gower,_1st_Marquess_of_Stafford) and Lady Louisa Egerton. He was educated at [Westminster School](/Westminster_School) and later at [Christ Church, Oxford](/Christ_Church,_Oxford), where he earned a [Master of Arts](/Master_of_Arts_(Oxford,_Cambridge,_and_Dublin)) in 1777.  

His mother, Lady Louisa, was a daughter of [Scroop Egerton, 1st Duke of Bridgwater](/Scroop_Egerton,_1st_Duke_of_Bridgwater), linking the Leveson‑Gower line to one of the richest landholdings in England. Through his father’s second marriage, he gained a half‑brother, [Granville Leveson‑Gower, 1st Earl Granville](/Granville_Leveson-Gower,_1st_Earl_Granville), who would later serve as Foreign Secretary.  

---  

## Earlier political career  

From 1779 to 1784, Sutherland represented the borough of [Newcastle‑under‑Lyme](/Newcastle-under-Lyme_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) in the House of Commons. He then moved to the county constituency of [Staffordshire](/Staffordshire_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), serving as its Member of Parliament between 1787 and 1799. In 1799, he entered the House of Lords via a **writ of acceleration** in his father’s junior title, **Baron Gower**.  

His early parliamentary work was characterised by a focus on fiscal matters and a willingness to align with the prevailing [Tory](/Tories_(British_political_party)) government, though he would later shift allegiances.  

---  

## Ambassador during French Revolution  

Between 1790 and 1792, Sutherland served as **British Ambassador to France**. He was appointed to Paris in June 1790 at the age of 32, succeeding [The Duke of Dorset](/John_Sackville,_3rd_Duke_of_Dorset). His tenure coincided with a period of extreme upheaval: [Louis XVI](/Louis_XVI) was under house arrest in the [Tuileries Palace](/Tuileries_Palace), and the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution) was reshaping the political landscape.  

Sutherland’s diplomatic inexperience was evident; his primary objective was to convey news from the French court back to Britain, often reporting seemingly trivial details. He struggled to comprehend the broader revolutionary currents, a shortcoming highlighted by the insurrection of 10 August 1792, when the [Paris Revolutionary Commune](/Paris_Commune_(1789%E2%80%931795)) overthrew the monarchy and led to the arrest of Louis XVI. Britain subsequently broke off diplomatic relations, and the embassy was closed, ending Sutherland’s ambassadorship.  

---  

## Later political career  

After returning to Britain, Sutherland declined offers of [Lord Steward of the Household](/Lord_Steward_of_the_Household) and [Lord‑Lieutenant of Ireland](/Lord-Lieutenant_of_Ireland). Instead, he accepted the post of **joint Postmaster General** in 1799, a position he held until 1801.  

A political realignment occurred in 1804 when he helped bring down the administration of [Henry Addington](/Henry_Addington). Following this, he switched from the [Tory](/Tories_(British_political_party)) to the [Whig](/Whigs_(British_political_party)) party. Though he remained active in public life, his involvement in high‑level politics waned after 1807, though he later expressed support for **Catholic Emancipation** and the **1832 Reform Act**.  

Militarily, he served as **Colonel** of the newly formed [Staffordshire Regiment of Gentlemen and Yeomanry](/Staffordshire_Yeomanry) from 1794 to 1800, personally commanding the [Newcastle‑under‑Lyme](/Newcastle-under-Lyme) Troop. He also held the honorary roles of [Lord Lieutenant of Staffordshire](/Lord_Lieutenant_of_Staffordshire) (1799–1801) and [Lord Lieutenant of Sutherland](/Lord_Lieutenant_of_Sutherland) (1794–1830).  

In 1830, he was invested as a **Knight of the Garter** and, the following year, was created **Duke of Sutherland**. His final public act was serving as treasurer of the [Salop Infirmary](/Royal_Salop_Infirmary) in [Shrewsbury](/Shrewsbury) in 1831.  

---  

## Wealth  

Sutherland’s inheritance included vast estates in [Staffordshire](/Staffordshire), [Shropshire](/Shropshire) and [Yorkshire](/Yorkshire). In 1803 he also succeeded to the enormous Bridgewater estates, which comprised the [Bridgewater Canal](/Bridgewater_Canal) and a premier art collection that included much of the [Orleans Collection](/Orleans_Collection). This inheritance, combined with the wealth of the [Leveson‑Gower family](/Leveson-Gower_family), made him the **wealthiest man in Britain**, and arguably the wealthiest individual in the world, during the early 19th century.  

Contemporary observers, such as diarist [Charles Greville](/Charles_Greville_(diarist)), described him as a “leviathan of wealth” and the “richest individual who ever died.” His London residence was [Lancaster House](/Lancaster_House) (formerly Stafford House), which remained the ducal seat until 1912.  

---  

## Development of Sutherland and Highland clearances  

The duke’s most infamous legacy stems from his involvement in the **Highland Clearances**, particularly the **Sutherland Clearances** of the early 19th century. The clearances, concentrated between 1811 and 1820, involved the systematic eviction of thousands of tenants from the interior of [Sutherland](/Sutherland) to make way for large‑scale sheep farming, which promised higher rents.  

In 1811, an Act of Parliament authorised the construction of roads in northern Scotland, contingent upon landowners financing half the cost. Sutherland seized the opportunity to build roads and bridges that had previously been virtually nonexistent in the region. Influenced by contemporary social and economic theories, he and his wife, [Elizabeth Leveson‑Gower, Duchess of Sutherland](/Elizabeth_Leveson-Gower,_Duchess_of_Sutherland), concluded that subsistence farming could not sustain the local population.  

The clearance process was often brutal. In 1813, tenants in the Strath of Kildonan resisted eviction, leading to a six‑week standoff that required the deployment of the army. In 1814, factor [Patrick Sellar](/Patrick_Sellar) oversaw the burning of roof timbers in Strathnaver to prevent re‑occupation; an elderly, bedridden woman perished six days later. The incident sparked a highly publicised trial in 1816, after which Sellar was acquitted, but the negative press continued to tarnish the duke’s reputation.  

Newspapers such as **[The Observer](/The_Observer)** ran sensational headlines in 1819, branding the period “the Devastation of Sutherland.” The clearances left a deep imprint on the cultural memory of the Highlands, inspiring Gaelic songs that condemned the duke’s policies.  

