## Legacy  

Sutherland’s legacy is bifurcated: on one hand, he was a patron of the arts, a builder of infrastructure, and a powerful landowner; on the other, his policies contributed to the dispossession and suffering of Highland communities. The **Highland Clearances** remain a painful chapter in Scottish history, and the duke’s role in them has kept his name alive in folk songs and protest literature.  

One of the most famous Gaelic protest songs, **Dùthaich Mhic Aoidh**, mocks the duke and his policies, reflecting the deep resentment felt by many Scots.  

In contemporary discourse, his monuments have been the focus of vandalism and debate, illustrating the ongoing tension between historical commemoration and social justice.  

